{
  "doc_id": "24287",
  "text": "Magge et al. [CITATION_1] tackle a difficult problem in evaluating the role of cytoreductive surgery and HIPEC in the management of patients with gastric cancer and peritoneal carcinomatosis. Close on the heels of a recently published randomized trial, this study demonstrates the survival benefit in selected patients with gastric cancer in a Western population. [CITATION_2] Despite aggressive surgical techniques and careful selection of patients with minimal peritoneal disease [median peritoneal carcinomatosis index (PCI) = 10], the 3-year survival in this cohort was a humbling 18 %. The group identified characteristics such as male gender, signet ring histology, incomplete cytoreduction, and multivisceral surgery as factors predicting either worse survival or progression of disease.",
